{ ⭐ How to Study This Course? GM Danyyil Dvirnyy's ambition is to help you build healthy habits through typical moves. To really benefit from this course, especially if you're a beginner or a casual player, we encourage you to go through it more than once. Find a method that works for you to tackle this course – and try to stick to it. You may: 🔹Learn a part or a chapter within a given timeframe a week, for instance, using spaced repetition until you have fully assimilated the good moves, habits, and principles. Once you feel comfortable, advance to the next part/chapter – possibly pausing the one you've just mastered to avoid overload.or 🔹'Woodpeck' the course – if you feel capable and have a more advanced level. To do so, go to the course settings and:1 in the Quiz drop-down menu, change 'After Learn' to 'Immediately'. This disables Learning mode, so every position becomes a test – you’ll need to find the correct move yourself. You might also consider setting Reps to 1 instead of the default 3. 2 under Schedule, choose 'Cyclical' and set your cycle end date. Read more on this method here. ⭐ In Learning Mode 🔹We suggest that you take a moment to think for yourself about the best continuation before pressing the 'Next' button. Ideally, you could also write down your candidate moves and thoughts – in a notebook or even in a private note within the course – so you can track your progress later. 🔹The author likes to introduce a position with its context, which is a great way to get acquainted with new openings. However, sometimes clickable moves appear in the introductory text, and clicking on them disrupts the author's explanations due to a limitation in Chessable’s Learning mode. In this case, we recommend simply refreshing the page ⟳. ⭐ Course Symbol Guide • ❌: indicates a mistake ? or a blunder ??; • ✕ : indicates an inaccuracy ?!; • ✅: indicates an equivalent move, sometimes presented as an alternative by the author; • ✓: indicates a suboptimal move: it can be a soft fail for Move Trainer or not. Note: It is possible that, at times, a symbol may differ slightly from the author's interpretation. In such cases, it is best to follow the human perspective. Have fun learning! The Chessable Team } 
1.--   *

