{ We're usually taught general principles at the beginning of our chess journey: control the center, develop our pieces, and castle – concepts every chess player has heard countless times. However, as you may have noticed, and as we’ll explore throughout this course: " Chess is a game full of exceptions. " That's why every rule presented here will include additional explanations to clarify the principle behind it. The goal is to deepen your understanding of these principles rather than blindly imitating ideas you don’t fully grasp. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "1a) Claim the Center, Take the Space"]
[Black "1a) Claim the Center, Take the Space"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ One of the first principles we are taught is to fight for the center. Let me expand on this, in order to gain a deeper understanding of this concept. The fight for the center is vital, as it will heavily influence the opening stage. If you have a stronger center, it means you will easily develop your their pieces, while, at the same time, making it harder for your opponent to develop their own pieces optimally i.e. on the best squares. That’s why taking space in the center with the pawns is so important when we get a chance to do so. Once we control the center, we can decide where to focus our actions, as we will have a pleasant choice thanks to our central advantage. Oftentimes, this principle is neglected by beginners, and we should be able to punish them by pushing our central pawns in the best way possible. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "1a) Claim the Center, Take the Space"]
[Black "1a) Example: Big center"]
[Result "*"]
