{ White intends to play [d2]-[d4] in one move. } Nf6 $1 { One of the key positions of open 1.e4 [e5] games. This is the most energetic move, based on a concrete line. } ( { The move ✕ } 1...d6?! { defends the [e5]-pawn in advance in case of [d2]-[d4], but is too passive, as it would leave the center for White eventually. } 2.d4 exd4 3.cxd4 { There is no way to keep fighting for the center, so Black is just worse. } 3...Bb4+ {(( 3...Bb6 would allow White to protect their center. We will see how in the next chapters. ))} 4.Nc3 { . Next is castle, and Black is too late. } ) ( { ✕ } 1...Qf6?! { , directly trying to prevent [d2]-[d4], but the queen will be exposed, developing so early in the game. } 2.d4! exd4 3.e5 { the consequence of developing the queen so early. } 3...Qg6 {(( 3...Nxe5?? is impossible as after 4.Qe2 d6 5.cxd4 Black would lose a piece.))} 4.cxd4 Bb4+ 5.Nc3 { . Black is still underdeveloped, as White is ready to castle, and ...[Qxg2]? would be met by [Rg1]. } ) 
2.d4  { The critical move. White can refrain from grabbing space in the center, too, but that's not our concern here. } exd4 $1 ( { ❌ } 2...Bb6? 3.dxe5! { among several good responses, this is the most precise. } 3...Nxe4 4.Qd5! { , and Black is clearly losing, as [f7] and [e4] are under attack. } ) 
3.cxd4  Bb4+ $1 { The point of Black's play! Now that Black already has an active knight on [e4], they will be able to create counterplay against White's center. } ( { ❌ } 3...Bb6?? { would be too passive, as after } 4.d5 { , Black must retreat their knight and cannot challenge White's center. } )  *

