{ When talking about 1.d4 [d5] structures, we need to understand that six pawns are fighting for control of the center: the c-, d-, and e-pawns for both White and Black. Therefore, both players should develop their pieces to let those three pawns fight for the center. } Nc6 $6 {[%cal Yc7c6]} {[%csl Rc6]} {[%csl Yc7]} { This is a surprisingly popular kind of move. Black develops the knight as they were playing 1.e4 [e5] positions, neglecting the fact that the [c7]-pawn is now unable to join the fight in the center. } ( { Instead of ✕ } 1...Nc6?! { , Black has many different good moves, among others: • } { ✓ } {1...Be7 , • ✅ 1...Bb4 , • or the direct ✅ 1...c5 , involving the c-pawn in the fight for the center. } )  *

