Nc6 $1 { This is the most energetic move. Black develops the knight, putting pressure on the [d4]-pawn. Preparing castling wouldn't make sense, as it is not a priority. } ( { — Also, how would you do that with Black? } 1...Nh6 { , really? } {1...Ne7 , 1...Be7 – would you play those move? — No. Closed positions change the rules of the developing game. " When the position is closed, we have more time to develop our pieces in the most ambitious way. " } ) 
2.Nf3  { White also plays the most logical move, as the other pieces will have to see where their best development will be. } Bd7 $1 { Again: when it comes to closed positions, things change, as we have more time to decide where to develop our pieces. ...[Bd7] is one of the key moves in this position, so once again, Black should prioritize it. } ( {(✅ alternative)} 2...Qb6 { is surprisingly enough another sensible move, developing the queen so early on an active square. } ) 
3.Be2  {[%cal Gd1d4]} { One of the strongest moves here. } ( { With the move ✕ } 3.Bd3 { , we may admit that the [b1]-[h7] diagonal would be a better for one the bishop, but for concrete reasons, it doesn't work here. } 3...cxd4 4.cxd4 Qb6 { , and White has some problems defending the [d4]-pawn. } )  *

