{ Here's another example of a closed position. Would you be surprised to learn that it comes from the Petrosian Variation of the King's Indian Defense? As we know now, in this case, we should understand how to develop our pieces in the best way, even if it costs us more time, as in a closed kind of position our opponent can't punish us hard for being undeveloped. } a5 $1 {[%cal Gb8a6]} {[%cal Ga6b4]} { We prevent [b2]-[b4]. Once the knight reaches [a6], Black will be flexible and will decide later whether to play [Nc5] or not. } ( { ✕ } 1...Bd7?! { is a somewhat clumsy move here. Apart from not being the best plan, it is also painful to watch this move being executed on the board. } ) ( { ✕ } 1...Bg4?! { doesn't make sense here, as after } 2.h3 { , Black would have to retreat, as } 2...Bxf3 3.Bxf3 { is not a good trade here. } ) ( { ✓ } 1...Nbd7 { is a decent move, although it doesn't really play against the [b2]-[b4] plan from White, and it closes the [c8]-bishop. } ) ( { ✓ } 1...Na6! { is a decent version of the ...[a7]-[a5] and ...[Na6] idea. Black will play ...[Nc5] and eventually follow up with [a7]-[a5]. } ) ( { The pawn break ✕ } 1...c6 { doesn't really achieve much here. } )  *

