[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "1c) Castle for King Safety"]
[Black "1c) Castle for King Safety"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Castling is one of those special moves we learn early and aim to execute during the opening phase of the game. However, we must understand that even if it's kinda cool to move two pieces in one move, it's not necessarily the best thing to do. There are supporters of castling, like the super GM from Russia Alexander Grischuk, and there are more flexible people who don't mind to play with an uncastled king. This last scenario is typical in the computer era, when people rely on their intuition not to follow this principle too closely. For example, several young Indian Grand Masters have an uncompromising style, where castling is just a remote option. There are two main purposes of castling: 🔹1 The first one is obviously putting your king to a safe place. The logic is the following: as the central files are going to be opened, our king is supposed to be on a flank, possibly guarded by those three pawns in front of him. As you may understand, if the center is closed, castling makes less sense, as the king might be safe or safer in the center, too. 🔹2 The second purpose is to activate our rooks quickly. Therefore, if the central files are opened, the rook } { (especially if we castle long) } { might be activated immediately along the d-file. That's another logical conclusion and, once again, if the central files are not opened, castling makes less sense, as the rooks won't be so active on closed files. Personally, I would recommend prioritizing castle, as it simplifies your game once you have your king safe, especially if you are at the beginning of your chess journey. Let's look at a few examples. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "1c) Castle for King Safety"]
[Black "1c) When Not to Castle"]
[Result "*"]
