{ Clearing your first rank is another step towards achieving a healthy position in the opening phase. As simple as it is, the purpose of getting out the minor pieces is actually oftentimes to make space for the rooks in order to put some heavy pressure that's why they are called heavy pieces. The rooks need space on the first rank, in order to be placed on the most promising files. We will see this concept in detail in the next chapter. We will see positions where a side connects the rooks, mostly because this should become an instinct in our games. As usual, chess has no absolute rules, but the habit of connecting the rooks is more useful than it seems. In this chapter, we will see how to do it quickly without losing time so that we can place the rooks on the best files as soon as possible. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "1d) Clear the First Rank, Connect the Rooks"]
[Black "1d) Example 1 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pp2bppp/4pn2/8/3N4/3B4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]

{ How should White clear their first rank? } 
1.Bf4 $1 {[%cal Ye6e5]} {[%cal Yd8c7]} {[%csl Gf4]} { An active diagonal for the bishop. } ( {(✅ alternative)} 1.b3!? { , preparing to develop the bishop on [b2], despite using an extra tempo. } 1...O-O 2.Bb2 { . Next is [Qe2], finally connecting the rooks. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.Bg5?! { is a typical 'developing' move. More often this move just allows Black to improve their position after [h6], when the bishop will eventually have to retreat to a worse diagonal. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.Be3?! { will allow some ...[Nd5] in the future. } ) O-O  ( { ❌ } 1...Qxd4?? { clearly loses to } 2.Bb5+ { , and Black loses their queen. } ) ( { ❌ } 1...e5? { , the fork is an illusion } 2.Bxe5 { , and White has not only won a pawn, but their minor pieces also dominate the center. } ) 
2.c3  {[%cal Gd1e2]} { A typical move in this structure, reinforcing the [d4]-knight and preparing [Qe2]. } a6  
3.Qe2 $1 {[%cal Ga1d1]} {[%cal Gf1e1]} {[%csl Rc8]} {[%csl Rd8]} { Black will have a hard time clearing their own eighth rank }  *

