{ What should be White's priority? The isolated central pawn has many characteristics, but its main advantage is that it provides more central squares for our minor pieces while limiting the opponent's piece activity. White should look for ways to develop their minor pieces first. } 
1.Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2]} {[%cal Gc1e3]} { A relatively slow developing move, but a healthy one. Next will be [Nc2], preparing [Be3]. } ( {(✅ alternative)} 1.Nbd2 { with [Nb3] next, White prepares to develop their minor pieces first. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.c4?! { White gains no benefit from opening the center, as Black is fully prepared and has active pieces of their own. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.Re1?! { is not the priority here. } 1...Qb6!? { would create immediate problems on [f2]. } ) ( { You may ask yourself: — But after } 1.Na3 { , can the opponent, with } 1...Bxa3 { destroy our queenside pawn structure? — No, because of the tactical resource } 2.Qa4+ Nbc6 3.Qxa3 { , and White is better. } )  *

