{ Exchanges are there from a very early stage of the game. However, chess in not checkers and we are not obliged to capture a piece only because we have the possibility to do so. In this second part of the course, I will present some pretty common exchange scenarios. Your goal is to be able to identify them and replicate them when necessary. Once again, chess is full of exceptions, so don't automatically copy them, but try to understand whether these exchanges are good or not. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "2a) Exchange Your Opponents' Strong Bishops"]
[Black "2a) Exchange Your Opponent’s Strong Bishops"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ In the opening phase, we should aim to develop our bishops to the most promising diagonals, making them more active. As discussed in the chapter on prophylaxis, it’s important to create space to retreat if they are attacked. Once securely positioned on the diagonal, a bishop becomes quite strong, as it takes under its control several important squares. This task of controlling many squares is the most valuable role a bishop can play. A wise strategy is to identify in the opposite camp such powerful bishops and exchange them when possible. In this chapter, we’ll explore a few examples where trading these bishops is a standard and effective idea. } 
1.--   *

