{ This is a possible development in the Colle-Zukertort opening from White. From my experience as a coach, people really struggle to understand how to deal with this [e5]-knight, supported by the [d4]- and [f4]-pawns. } c4 $3 { This is not the main point of the example, but tactics take priority, and Black has a strong tactical solution here. Black exploits the X-ray action of the [b7]-bishop against the white queen on [f3]. Note: The X-ray idea refers to a piece exerting influence through an intervening pawn or, more rarely, another piece. For example, here the bishop on [b7] is attacking the queen on [f3], with the [d5]-pawn in between. } ( { ❌ } 1...Nxe5? {(is a move one should avoid playing unless there are concrete ideas for example, jumping on [e4] afterward. Here, however, after)} 2.fxe5 ± { , White transformed their [e5]-knight into a strong [e5] watershed, which will allow White to bring more pieces on the kingside. } ) ( { ❌ } 1...Ne8!? { . Preparing both ...f5 and ...Nd6 is actually a typical resource here. Since White poses no immediate threats, this maneuver is not necessary at the moment. } {( ❌ 1...cxd4? is generally a poor decision, as 2.exd4 this exchange only improves White's situation in the center. Black exchanged their strong [c5]-pawn for White's [e3]-pawn. )} {( The move ❌ 1...Nd7? doesn't really prepare [f6], as the lights squares along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal, together with the [f7]- and [e6]-weak squares, allow White to perform a classical combination: 2.Nxd7 Qxd7 3.dxc5 bxc5 . Now that both bishops are opened, White can start the spectacular combination: 4.Bxh7+ Kxh7 5.Qh3+! Kg8 6.Bxg7 Kxg7 ((More stubborn and less poetic would be 6...f5 when after 7.Rf3! , and White has a strong attack.)) 7.Qg4+ Kh7 8.Rf3 , and White is winning. )} {( ❌ 1...g6 makes some sense, although it weakens the long [a1]-[h8] diagonal. )} ) 
2.Nxc6  ( { ❌ } 2.Be2? { loses a piece after } 2...c3! 3.Bxc3 Nxe5! 4.fxe5 Ne4! { , and White loses the tactical battle. } ) Bxc6  
3.Be2  { White cannot capture on [c4], because of the discovered attack on Black's queen. } ( { If ❌ } 3.bxc4 dxc4 { , the X-ray mentioned below turns into a double attack: a discovered attack on the queen and an attack on the [d3]-bishop. Whatever White plays, for example, } 4.e4 { , they lose a piece, } 4...cxd3 { . } ) b5  {[%cal Ga7a5]} {[%csl Bb5]} {[%csl Bc4]} {[%csl Yd2]} {[%csl Ye2]} { And Black will expand on the queenside with a big advantage. }  *

