{ This is a scenario coming from an Alapin Sicilian. When White has an [e5]-pawn, the possibility of building the [Bd3]-[Qe4] battery should come to mind, as Black can't place a knight on [f6] because of the pawn on [e5]. Let's explore Black's options. } Rxd3 $3 { This idea should come to mind in similar positions, as Black resolves their weaknesses along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal once and for all by eliminating White's most dangerous piece. } ( { Capturing the pawn allows White to keep to d3-bishop alive after ❌ } 1...Bxa4 2.Nd4! { . Once we understand the priority of the position, we can easily identify these moves as the best in the position. } 2...Bc6 { , stopping [Qe4], but White can renew the threat with } 3.Bc2 { , maintaining the initiative, intending to play [Qd3]. } ) ( { Starting with ...Nc4 eliminates the possibility of playing ...Nb3 later on. ✓ } 1...Nc4 2.Bc1 Rxd3 3.Qxd3 Bxa4 4.g4 { , and White has counterplay with [g5], followed by [Kh1]-[Rg1]. } ) ( { ✕ } 1...Bc6 { is another way to stop [Qe4], but after } 2.Nd4 Bd5 { not only the [d3]-bishop is alive, but after } 3.Nb5! { , White acquires extra threats thanks to their potential knight jumps. } ) ( { Black can't even think about removing the pawn from e5 by playing ❌ } 1...f6? { , because after } 2.exf6 { , White is completely winning. } ) 
2.Qxd3  Bxa4  { Black is more active thanks to ...[Qc4] and ...[Nb3] ideas. } 
3.Nd4  {[%cal Gc7c4]} {[%cal Ga5b3]} { Defending against both ideas. } Qd7 $1 {[%cal Ga5b3]} { Renewing the threat of ...[Nb3]. }  *

