1.dxc5 $1 { A typical reaction in this kind of position. Rubinstein's idea was to postpone the development of the [f8]-bishop exactly for this fact. White gains a tempo, as Black has to recapture on [c5]. } ( { In a similar fashion, ✓ } 1.Nbd2 { allows Black to release the tension in a favorable version. } 1...cxd4 2.exd4 { , and the knight on [d2] can be misplaced. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.Bb2 { leaves the [b1]-knight flexible, although still allowing } 1...cxd4 2.exd4 { . Here, White has an extra option of [c4]-[Nc3]. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.a3 { is another possibility, stopping any ...[Nb4] and remaining flexible with minor pieces development. } ) Bxc5  
2.Bb2  {[%cal Ga2a3]} {[%cal Gb3b4]} {[%cal Gb1d2]} {[%csl Rc6]} { This structure is considered more promising for White, compared to the line with 1...cxd4 2.exd4 . }  *

