{ Throughout his career, Rubinstein experimented with different approaches to handling this kind of scenario. Later, Rubinstein improved on his [a2]-[a4] idea with the following move. } 
1.a3 $1 { This is a healthier move, positionally speaking. The main idea is to continue with the exchanges on [c4]. } ( { White could try to release the tension in the center by playing ✓ } 1.cxd5 { . In this version, Black can recapture both the c-pawn and the e-pawn, as their pawn structure is really solid. } 1...exd5 2.Bd3 { . This would be a fairly logical transformation of the initial position. Nowadays, the Carlsbad structure is fashionable, and there are chances for both sides. } ) ( { Let's take a look at the most logical move for White. The basic idea here is that if White develops their bishop to d3, ✅ } 1.Bd3 { , they will have to recapture on [c4], losing a tempo: } 1...dxc4 2.Bxc4 b5 3.Bd3 {(( or 3.Be2 . ))} 3...Bb7 { . Black will be ready to play [c5], maybe kicking in a [h7]-[h6] first, and will have a great position. } ) ( { Nowadays, engines have come up with a sensational new idea, yet to be used at the highest level: ✅ } 1.h4!! { . This is a multipurpose move: White is ready to ignore [h7]-[h6], as they will be able to leave the [g5]-bishop hanging, as ...[hxg5] would open the h-file. The other idea is to prepare the rook lift [Rh3]–g3, building the [Ne5]-jump. At the same time, White is not wasting a tempo on the light-squared bishop moves, so after } 1...dxc4 2.Bxc4 { would come in one move. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.a4!? { was Rubinstein's try for a short period, but his positional intuition probably suggested that this can't be the right approach. Even if he scored well with this prophylactic idea against Black ...[b7]-[b5], the weakening of the [b4]-square should allow Black to have a good position, with ...[Qa5]-...[Bb4] and ...[c6]-[c5] available. } ) dxc4  ( { ✅ } 1...b6 { is probably the best move, and after } 2.Bd3 Bb7 {(( 2...dxc4 doesn't make too much sense, as Black would also lose a tempo for [b6]-[b5]. 3.Bxc4 ))} 3.O-O { , and Black will have to fight for the center eventually, although Black's position is pretty solid anyway. } ) 
2.Bxc4  b5  
3.Ba2 $1 {[%cal Ga2b1]} {[%csl Rh7]} { After [Bb1], White would form a strong battery on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal, and it's going to be more difficult for Black to fight for the center, as he would be responsible for those extra threats against [h7]. }  *

