[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "⭐ Part 3: Patterns of Prophylaxis"]
[Black "What Is My Opponent's Idea? – Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ The term prophylaxis means anticipating and preventing the opponent's plans or tactics before they can be executed. Asking yourself, ‘What is my opponent's idea?’ is one of the most important habits to develop, especially as a beginner. From the very first moves of a game, we must be aware of our opponent's threats. Here, I have selected five patterns that are easy to remember and apply in your own games. I also aim to provide a deeper understanding of these principles, which are often presented as absolute rules. Once again, chess is a game of exceptions, so it is crucial to grasp the reasoning behind an idea. Knowing that a possibility exists is one thing – understanding when and how to use it correctly is another. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "3a) Support Your Center with Small Pawn Moves"]
[Black "3a) Support Your Center With Small Pawn Moves"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Once we have managed to control the center, the best way to maintain our pawns is usually to keep them side by side. Two white pawns on [e4] and [d4] control a wide range of squares, allowing our pieces to develop comfortably while restricting the opponent’s development. We should only consider pushing one of these pawns if our opponent has disrupted the structure. For example, if Black challenges our [e4]-[d4] center with a ...[c5] break, pushing [d5] might become a strong option, as Black's c-pawn can no longer contest it. Pushing central pawns prematurely is generally unwise, as it exposes the center to pawn breaks and creates weak squares. In this chapter, we will explore how to keep a strong center when it is challenged, particularly against piece-based attacks such as bishop pins. } 
1.--   *

