{ Our opponents often expand on a particular side of the board. In my experience, distinguishing between a healthy expansion and a positional weakness isn’t always obvious. To determine whether we should prevent such expansions, I suggest asking two key questions: 🔹Will it be easy to challenge these advanced pawns later? 🔹Can we exploit the weakened squares in the next few moves? If the answer to either question is ‘yes,’ it's usually better to focus on improving our position rather than stopping the expansion. However, if both answers are ‘no,’ then preventing the expansion becomes a priority. } 
