{ White played [a2]-[a3] and intends taking space on the queenside with [b2]-[b4]. Black has several options here. } a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4]} {[%cal Ga5a4]} {[%csl Bb4]} {[%csl Ba4]} { It is possible to play this move both to prevent [b2]-[b4] and to eventually take some space by advancing [a5]-[a4] and add some plans such as [Na5]-[Nb3]. } ( { ✓ } 1...cxd4 2.cxd4 a5 { , including the moves [cxd4] - [cxd4] allows White to get a nice square for the knight, so it's not a good idea generally. } 3.Nc3 ) ( { ✅ } 1...f6! { is one of the best reactions. Black ignores the [b2]-[b4] and puts more pressure on White's center. With White's king still on [e1], opening the f-file can bring Black some additional ideas. } ) ( { ✕ } 1...c4?! { is generally a poor move, as now White's center is not under pressure and White can simply develop, without having to take into consideration the various openings of central lines. } )  *

