{ What is Black's idea, and what should White do about it? } 
1.Bb3 $1 { Black was actually threatening both ...[Nxe4] or ...[d6]-[d5]. A general rule of thumb is to prevent pawn breaks when we have more space. In order to do so, our 'broken' pawn should be able to advance if touched, making the pawn break ineffective. } ( { ✕ } 1.a4 { would fight against the wrong pawn push. } 1...d5! { , and Black gains some important space in the center by eliminating the [e4]-pawn. } ) d5 $6 { This move would now fail to reach its goal. } ( { The move ✓ } 1...b5 { is generally decent if there is a White knight on [c3]. } 2.a4! { , a typical break. } {(( 2.e5 is also pretty strong here.))} 2...b4 { with a knight on [c3], Black would be attacking it, but here this move is pointless. } 3.Re1 { , Black weakened their queenside for no good reason. } ) 
2.e5  {[%cal Rg7e5]} {[%csl Gd4]} {[%csl Rd5]} {[%csl Ge5]} {[%csl Rg7]} { And white keeps their space advantage. }  *

