{ One of the typical positions in the Najdorf Sicilian. How should White deal with the possibility of Black playing ...[b7]-[b5]? } 
1.Be3 $1 { Not the absolute best move, but a healthy developing one. } ( { ✓ } 1.a4?! { would be premature here, as Black can make use of the weakened [b4]-square. } 1...Nc6 ) ( { The move ✓ } 1.f4?! { doesn't accomplish much, as Black can simply develop with a move like } 1...Nc6 { . } ) ( { ✓ } 1.Bg5 { is definitely possible, but Black should both be careful of [Nxe4] tactic and [Bxf6]-[Nd5] doesn't achieve much, as after } 1...Be6 {((The typical Bg5-Be7 tension based tactical 'trick' with 1...Nxe4?! doesn't work. 2.Bxe7 Nxc3 3.Bxd8 Nxd1 4.Be7 and Black will not have enough compensation for the exchange. 4...Nxb2 5.Bxf8 Kxf8 . ))} 2.Bxf6 Bxf6 3.Nd5 Bg5 { , Black's bishop on [g5] is quite active. } ) b5 $6 { This would be inaccurate here. } 
2.a4 $1 { Challenging the structure [a6]-[b5]. } b4  { We saw the generally with the knight on [c3], this move should justify Black's idea. } 
3.Nd5 $1 { If not for this move, Black's idea would be decent. Now Black's position is much better, as the [d5]-knight is pretty strong. } Nxd5 $6 { A bad move to illustrate White's idea. } 
4.Qxd5  {[%cal Ge3a7]} {[%csl Ra8]} {[%csl Ge3]} { And Black is immediately lost, as the [e3]-bishop controls the [a7]-square. }  *

