{ Black has everything set to play ...[b7]-[b5]. Should White play [a4]-[a5], discouraging it, or will Black push the b-pawn anyway? } 
1.a5 $1 { I would say that in most cases this is the right approach. Obviously, it depends on the position, but unless White can't stop ...[b7]-[b5], [a4]-[a5] will disrupt Black's structure on the queenside and the activity along the b-file will hardly be enough. } ( { ✓ } 1.Qd2!? { is also possible, preparing [Bh6]. In my opinion, here after } 1...b5 { , it is important not to take on [b5]. } 2.Bh6! {(( The point is that after 2.axb5 axb5 3.Bh6 b4 4.Bxg7 Kxg7 5.Nd1 Black can jump with 5...Nb5 getting some counterplay. ))} 2...b4 3.Bxg7 Kxg7 4.Nd1 { and the [a4]-pawn is preventing Black from activating their [c7]-knight. } ) b5  
