{ Castling long for White means the king moves from [e1] to [c1] and the rook moves from [a1] to [d1], positioning itself on an open or semi-open file. This allows the rook to become more active and involved in the game, especially if there is tension on the d-file or in the center. The king is generally safer on [c1] than on [e1]. But by playing [Kb1], the monarch is tucked safely behind three pawns, making it even less vulnerable. } 
1.Kb1  {[%csl Ga2]} {[%csl Gb2]} {[%csl Gc2]} { While [Kb1] may cost a tempo in concrete positions, I still consider it a generally healthy habit, as it's rarely a mistake. }  *

