1.Kb1 $1 {[%csl Ga2]} {[%csl Gb2]} {[%csl Gc2]} { This is the most useful move here. White's king will now be safer behind all three long castled pawns and White will also get more information about what are Black's plans. White is going to be ready anticipating potential shenanigans. } ( { ✕ } 1.a4? { wouldn't make sense here, as White is basically weakening their castle for the sake of challenging Black's [a6]-[b5] structure. Both ...[b7]-[b5] and even the ugly ...[bxa4] would be in Black's favor. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.a3?! { is a passive move we want to avoid as a habit. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.Nh3 { is definitely possible, but we are not sure yet how to develop our pieces on the kingside, so it's not the most flexible move. } )  *

