{ In this slow Pirc /Modern type of position, Black has just challenged White's center. How should White react? } 
1.h3 $1 { A strong patient move supporting the center, preventing any ...[Bg4]. Black has no immediate way to improve their situation in the center. The two ways that come to mind are the immediate [d5], or [cxd4]-[exd4] and [d5], but neither works. } ( { ✓ } 1.d5 { this would play in White's favor, as after } 1...Ne7 2.c4 Nd7 {(, Black would have a typical play with [f7]-[f5], while White would be quite slow creating assets on the queenside where they are supposedly stronger.)} ) ( { ✓ } 1.dxe5?! { is possible, but is definitely not an ambitious move and, more importantly, quite an unhealthy impulse. } 1...Nxe5 2.Nxe5 dxe5 {(, White gives up their supremacy in the center, exchanging their strong [d4]-pawn for the [d6] not e5! counterpart.)} ) exd4 $2 ( { ✕ } 1...d5? 2.exd5 { , and black will lose the [e5]-pawn afterward. } ) ( { Apparently, a timid move such as ✓ } 1...Bd7 { turns out to be the best way for Black to improve their position in this situation. } ) 
2.cxd4  Nb4  { This response leads nowhere. } ( { ✕ } 2...d5 3.e5 Ne4 4.Nc3! 4...Nxc3 5.bxc3 { , and once again the [h3] move turns out to be useful here. } ) 
3.Bf1  {[%cal Gb1c3]} { With [Nc3] next, White's center is in great shape. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "Part 3 Test"]
[Black "3) Test #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qrnk1/pp2bppp/2p1bn2/3p4/3P4/2NBPP2/PPQ1NBPP/3RR1K1 w - - 0 1"]

{ In this typical Carlsbad structure, White's thematic pawn break is the move [e4], taking space in the center. Black's typical counter break is the move ...[c6]-[c5], now that White's pawn is on [f3], so that Black could target the e-pawn. Is it the moment to play [e4], or does White have time to prepare it? } 
1.h3 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4]} {[%cal Rf6g4]} { This is a must-know textbook prophylactic move, avoiding any ...[Ng4] business. } ( { ✕ } 1.e4?! { would be premature, as after } 1...dxe4 2.fxe4 Ng4! { , would deprive White of their strong dark-squared bishop, as [Bg3] would be followed by ...[Ne3], forking the queen and the e-rook. } )  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "Part 3 Test"]
[Black "3) Test #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/bpp2pp1/p1np1n1p/4p3/4P3/1BPP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 0 1"]

{ The Giuoco Piano, literally meaning 'Slow Play', is a fashionable opening nowadays. However, [d3]-[d4] remains a standard plan, as fighting for the center is important. How should White proceed? } 
1.Nbd2 $1 { A patient move, preparing [Nf1]-[Be3], and only then can White consider preparing [d3]-[d4]. Playing slowly here is a wise strategy. [g7]-[g5] wouldn't now be as effective as with White's pawn on [h3]. } ( { The preparatory ✕ } 1.h3? { would be a terrible mistake here! } 1...g5!! { , now the [h3]-pawn would become bait for Black's attack, and with ...[g5]-[g4], ...[Rg8] incoming, White would have to worry about their king safety. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.d4?! { is clearly untimely too, as Black would play the typical } 1...Bg4 { White's center is under serious pressure. } )  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "Part 3 Test"]
[Black "3) Test #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r6r/1p1bkppp/p3p3/2npP3/3N1P1P/5B2/PPP3P1/2KR3R w - - 0 1"]

{ This is a typical structure from the Steinitz Variation of the French Defense. Find Black's idea and how to counter it. } 
1.g4 $1 { White has to be careful not to overextend on the kingside. However, in this case, Black's idea is ...[h7]-[h5], blocking the kingside. [g2]-[g4] is a multipurpose move, stopping ...[h5] and preparing [f5] later. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "Part 3 Test"]
[Black "3) Test #6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/1p2bpp1/2p1nn1p/p2p4/3P3B/2NBPP2/PPQ1N1PP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]

{ We know that Black's idea to counter [f2]-[f3] is the ...[c6]-[c5] break. We also know that White needs some extra preparation for the [e3]-[e4] break, with moves like [h2]-[h3]. Do you see the other Black's idea? Find it and evaluate the possible of taking extra time against it. } 
1.a4 $5 {[%cal Rb7b5]} {[%cal Gh2h3]} {[%cal Gh4f2]} {[%cal Ge3e4]} { A surprising decision, but quite an effective one. The 'modern' ...[c6]-[c5] idea is actually improved by the move ...[b5]-[b4], followed by ...[c6]-[c5], as Black would take extra space and remove an important supporter of White's center the [c3] Knight. That's why, this seemingly unhealthy move White is weakening the [b4]-square, gains some important time, as Black now needs more pieces to prepare ...[b7]-[b5]. The ...[c6]-[c5] break is now hard to achieve, as the [b5]-square would be available for White pieces, with annoying moves, such as [Bb5], disrupting Black's coordination. Once White managed to stop ...[b7]-[b5], they can go back to prepare [e3]-[e4] with moves like [h2]-[h3] and [Bf2]. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "Part 3 Test"]
[Black "3) Test #7 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qrbk1/1bp2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 1"]

{ In this position from Zaitsev Ruy López, Black just played ...[Bf8] and looks ready for some strike in the center, as White is currently slightly undeveloped. Is Black actually threatening anything? How should White proceed? } 
1.d5 $1 { By playing this move immediately, White is intending to build a strong chain with [b3]-[c4]. As the knight is still on [b1], there will be a possibility to jump to the most natural [c3] later on. } ( { A. ✕ } 1.a3?! { is a move to prevent the idea of [exd4] - [cxd4] - [Nb4], but it's too slow here. } 1...d5! 2.Nxe5 Nxe5 3.dxe5 Nxe4 { , and White's can't allow giving up their light-squared bishop for the [e4] Knight. } ) ( {(B. ✅ alternative)} 1.Nbd2!? { . A typical developing move, reinforcing White center. Let's see if Black has some ideas to break immediately. } {( 𓈓b1. 1...g6!? Black can keep the status quo, and it's not clear how White should proceed, as Black is preparing an improved version of the [d5] break, with the [f8]-bishop now ready to join the battle via [g7]. After, 2.d5 , White would still have to go for this, but the knight on [d2] would be a little more passive compared to [c3]-square. ((The much desired 2.Nf1?! with the idea of [Ng3] doesn't work: 2...exd4 3.cxd4 Nb4 and White can't handle everything at once. )))} {( 𓈓b2. 1...exd4?! 2.cxd4 . This inclusion doesn't bring Black any benefits. 2...d5 (( 2...Nb4 3.Bb1 , White has a nice place for their bishop and will later kick the [b4]-knight away with [b4], keeping their strong [e4]-[d4] center.)) 3.e5 . We should be familiar with the fact that if Black doesn't have the [Ne4] jump here as an option, White is better. )} {( 𓈓b3. 1...d5!? . A typical pawn break, trying to eliminate the center. 2.Nxe5! Initiating a typical sequence. () 2...Nxe5 3.dxe5 Rxe5 ((If 3...Nxe4 4.Nxe4 dxe4 5.Bf4! , and White will collect the [e4]-pawn, while Black is not quick enough to attack the [e5]-pawn.)) 4.f4! , White takes more space, preparing [e5]. 4...Re8 5.e5 . Once again, if Black doesn't have any immediate counters, this expansion should grant White an edge. 5...Bc5+ 6.Kh1 Ne4 7.Nxe4 dxe4 8.Qe2 , White is slightly better, as [e4] is weak once again. )} {( C. ❌ 1.h3? doesn't make any sense here, as no potential [Bg4] are threatening the [e4]-[d4] center. )} ) Ne7  ( { Even if the move ✅ } 1...Na5 { fights against the [b3]-[c4] plan, Black would position the knight in a dangerous square, as White could proceed with [Nbd2] and [b4]. } ) 
2.b3  {[%cal Gc3c4]} {[%cal Rf7f5]} {[%csl Re8]} { Black will have to provide some more space for their minor pieces. }  *

