{ Improvement is a fundamental concept in chess. Often, refining even a small detail in your position is the best thing you can do. Before engaging in battle, it is advisable to optimize the placement of your pieces. In the fourth part of this course, we will explore how to improve each of our five pieces. By the end, you’ll encounter positions where you must decide which piece needs improvement the most and figure out how to achieve that – hopefully, with new skills gained from this training! } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "4a) Reroute Your Knight to the Outpost"]
[Black "4a) Reroute the Knight to the Outpost"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Knights thrive on outposts. Even if it takes time to reach one, the effort is often worthwhile, as an outposted knight can become extremely powerful – especially if it cannot be exchanged. As we will see, improving a knight’s position can change the course of a game, so always watch for strong squares where your knights can settle. And don’t forget: they can jump! } 
1.--   *

