[White "4a) Reroute Your Knight to the Outpost"]
[Black "4a) Example 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/4bppp/p2p4/1p2p3/4P3/N1P5/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]

1.Nc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2e3]} {[%cal Ge3d5]} {[%cal Gc2b4]} {[%cal Gb4d5]} { Rerouting the knight to an uncontested outpost is most of the times a clever idea. Here, we have a smooth example, where the [d5]-knight will be dominant, typical of the Pelikán and Kalashnikov openings. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "4a) Reroute Your Knight to the Outpost"]
[Black "4a) Example 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pp1n1pbp/2p2np1/4p3/P3P3/2N1BN2/1PP1BPPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ This position can arise from a Pirc structure, where the [c6]-pawn covers the [d5]-square and limits the [c3]-knight. Although White developed with [Be2], which usually is considered a quiet approach, there is an idea that is strong for White. } 
1.Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4]} {[%cal Gc4d6]} {[%csl Gc6]} { d6 is White's dream square, so what about jumping directly towards it? } ( { ✕ } 1.O-O { is not a priority here. } 1...Qe7! { a good prophylaxis against the [Nd2]-[Nc4] idea. } {(( 1...O-O 2.Qd6! , and it's not so easy to kick away White's Queen. 2...Ne8?! 3.Qa3 , and Black's position is clumsy.))} 2.Nd2 2...Nc5! { now Black has this move. } 3.Nc4 O-O { Now Black will have the [Ne6]-[Nd4] maneuver. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.Qd6 { leads nowhere after } 1...Bf8! ) ( { ✕ } 1.Bc4!? { is possible, improving the bishop. However, this is not exploiting the position to the maximum. } ) O-O  
2.Nc4  Qe7  
3.Qd6 $1 {[%cal Yd7c5]} { Having played this maneuver early, ...[Nc5] is not possible. White is now significantly better. }  *

