{ In the Sicilian, Black can sometimes play schemes with ...[e5], blocking the center, but weakening the [d5]-square. } ( { Here, for example, it is a typical position from the } 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5!? { move order. } ) 
1.Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2f1]} {[%cal Gf1e3]} {[%cal Ge3d5]} { Once again, with the center being closed, starting this knight maneuver early oftentimes is a clever idea. } ( { ✅ } 1.O-O Nf6 { and now the [f3]-knight doesn't have a clear path towards [d5]. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.h3 { is not necessary here, as ...[Bg4] isn't really a threat. There is no center to protect at the moment. } ) ( { The tempting ✕ } 1.Nd5?! { is a typical mistake, as after } 1...Nf6 { , Black would immediately exchange a few pieces with ...[Be6] to follow. } )  *

