{ A variation of the structure we saw in this chapter. Black has a knight on [g6], but White has different possibilities. What would you choose as the continuation? } 
1.Nc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2b4]} {[%cal Gb4d5]} { Once again, this should be the priority. } ( { ✓ } 1.h4?! { doesn't really do much, as after } 1...h5 { , the [h4]-pawn is simply weak and there is little reward from the [g5]-square. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.O-O { is actually too slow, as after } 1...Be7 2.Nc2 O-O { , Black is ready to strike with ...[f7]-[f5]. } 3.Nb4 f5 ↑ { , opening up the position for Black's light squares, such as [f5], [e4], [g4]. } ) Be7  ( { ✓ } 1...a5!? { is a clever response. } 2.Na3! { would be a great move here! White prepares [c3]-[c4] next, fighting back and looking for a great square for White's knight. } ) 
2.Nb4  O-O  
3.Nd5  f5  { Now White has time to do useful things. Besides having the options of [Nb6] and [Bb6], White can actually capture on [e7], or even castle long. } 
4.O-O-O $5 {[%cal Gd1d8]} {[%csl Gc1]} {[%csl Gd3]} {[%csl Gd5]} { An extra option, having already placed the knight on [d5]. With the rook on [d1], White can target the weak [d6]-pawn. }  *

