{ A more sophisticated pattern is presented in this chapter: evacuating your king from a potential warzone in advance. This is a very healthy habit to develop, as it not only improves your king's position but also frees your hands to control the side of the board where the action will unfold. If you think about it, castling serves these two purposes. However, castling is not always possible in a given position. Therefore, we should know when to achieve the same effect artificially. This pattern generally applies to closed positions, but sometimes, the urgency of improving the king’s safety may suggest that we adopt it even in more open positions. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "4c) Steer Your King to the Safe Side"]
[Black "4c) Example 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3qnbkn/r1rb1ppp/1p1p4/pPpPpNP1/P1P1P2P/2NB1Q2/3B1P1K/6RR w - - 0 1"]

{ A game from the legendary World Champion Vassily Smyslov. As he wrote in his book In Search of Harmony, let's see how White achieves harmony here. Black is completely out of counterplay, therefore White has time to improve their pieces before opening the position. Clearly improving his king is a priority here. } 
1.Kg2 $1 {[%cal Gg2c2]} g6  
2.Kf1 $1 { Leaving the knight on [f5] on prise is typical for Ruy López positions, where similarly the queenside is blocked. It's generally too dangerous for Black to capture on [f5]. } Bc8  ( { In this positional sacrifice, there is almost no risk – though Black is a piece up, they are totally lost ❌ } 2...gxf5 3.exf5 ) 
3.h5  Rab7  
4.Rh2  Ra7  
5.Ke1  Rab7  
6.Kd1  Ra7  
7.Kc2  Rab7  
8.Kb3  Ra7  
9.Qg3  {[%cal Gf2f4]} {[%csl Gb3]} { Since he made his king safe, White prepares [f2]-[f4]. } Rab7  
10.f4  exf4  
11.Bxf4  Ra7  
12.Nd1  {[%cal Yd1e3]} {[%cal Ye3g4]} {[%cal Yf4d2]} {[%cal Yd2c3]} { The threat is [Ne3]-[g4] and [Bd2]-[c3]. Black is lost. } gxf5  
13.exf5  Ng7  
14.Ne3  h6  
15.f6  { Typical Smyslov's game: all moves are clear and simple. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "4c) Steer Your King to the Safe Side"]
[Black "4c) Example 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r2rk/2p1qp1p/1p1p1pn1/p4Q2/2P2P2/2R1P1P1/PPBR3P/5K2 w - - 0 1"]

{ This structure can generally be reached from the Budapest gambit positions. Another example, this time with a more opened board. However, here Black doesn't have counterplay, either. } 
1.Ke1 $1 {[%cal Ge1c1]} { The king heads towards the safe part. } Qe6  
2.Qh5  Qe7  
3.Kd1  Rg7  
4.Kc1  {[%csl Gc1]} Nf8  
5.Bf5  Re8  
6.g4 $1 { White went on to opening the kingside and won in Alekhine - Yates, Semmering 1926. }  *

