{ Rooks, along with the queen, are the pieces capable of creating the most dangerous threats, which is why they are referred to as 'heavy pieces.' Rooks thrive on open or semi-open files, where they can create these threats. But why do we prioritize this principle in the opening phase? Among other reasons, it's to position our rooks on the files where they have the most potential to become dangerous. However, if the opportunity arises, we can improve our rooks without strictly following the usual routine. This is why we call ‘unorthodox’ the pattern presented in this chapter. By activating our rooks on the file they are already placed on, we can save time and create threats more quickly. Sometimes, our bishops can be considered 'developed' by simply staying on their initial squares, as long as they don’t block the rooks. Being creative in improving our rooks not only enhances our general understanding but can also bring aesthetic satisfaction. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "4d) Unorthodox Ways to Improve Your Rooks"]
[Black "4d) Example 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp2nppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/P1P5/2P2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ In this extremely popular Winawer starting position, White has different possibilities, but with the center closed, we should think about developing our rooks creatively on semi-opened files. } 
1.h4 $5 {[%cal Gh1h3]} {[%cal Gh3g3]} {[%cal Gh3a3]} { If the rook lands on [g3] or on [f3], those will become semi-open files for the rook, as the white pawns will be behind the rook. }  *

