{ This is a position from a line I played as White as a kid. White threatens [e4]-[e5]. How should Black respond, and more importantly, how should the rooks be involved? } d5 $1 { This is the modern approach. } ( { ✓ } 1...h5!? { is the standard way of meeting [e4]-[e5], granting the [g4]-square for the knight. } 2.e5 Ng4 { . Now the knight will hardly be in danger, as the opening of the h-file would be too much. } 3.Ne4! {(( 3.Bxg4 would be a terrible move. 3...hxg4 . ))} 3...Bxe4 4.Qxe4 Rc8 { . Black activated both of their rooks, although White has the bishop pair. } ) 
2.exd5  O-O $3 {[%cal Ga8d8]} {[%cal Gf8e8]} { When I looked again at this line after many years, I was amazed by the power behind Black's moves. The development is more important than pawns here! } 
3.dxe6  ( { ✅ } 3.d6 Qd7 4.Bxb7 Qxb7 { , and the [d6]-pawn will eventually fall. } ) Rad8  
4.Qe2  ( { ❌ } 4.exf7+?? Rxf7 { , and White's queen is in trouble. } ) Rfe8 $1 {[%csl Bd8]} {[%csl Be8]} {[%csl Ye2]} {[%csl Ye6]} { The centralized Black rooks look dangerous. }  *

