{ We're all taught early on that we shouldn't develop the queen in the opening phase. As the most valuable piece, she can become a target, losing time and taking away development opportunities from other pieces. With the board still crowded, finding a safe yet active square is challenging. To keep the queen comfortable, she is often best placed on the edges of the board } { (a4-[h4] for White, [a5]-[h5] for Black) } { or on files unlikely to open. A more advanced approach is to eliminate potential attackers, securing her an active post closer to the center. This idea appears in the Alapin Sicilian, after ... } 
1.e4  c5  
2.c3  d5  
3.exd5  Qxd5  {[%csl Yb1]} {[%csl Gd5]} { ...the queen is surprisingly safe on [d5], as there’s no knight to harass her. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "4e) Make Your Queen Feel Comfortable"]
[Black "4e) Example 1 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/1bqnbppp/pp1ppn2/8/1PPNP3/P1N1BP2/3QB1PP/2RR2K1 b - - 0 1"]

{ A typical configuration of pieces from the Hedgehog structure. The queen on [c7] is often misplaced and is automatically repositioned. } Qb8 $1 {[%cal Rc1c7]} { There is nothing concrete now, but with the central files potentially opening up, we should generally avoid having our Queen on the same file of the opponent's rooks. Here, the queen will feel safe and connected to the rest of the pieces. Subsequently, once the files will open, the queen will be able to join the fight. }  *

