{ This is a position from the Semi-Slav Opening that can be reached via different move orders. In this position, Black should connect the rooks. To do so, Black should find a place for their queen. How do we do it? } Qc7 $1 { A more cautious move, connecting the rooks. } ( { ✕ } 1...Bd6 { would be a more ambitious way of developing our pieces, to play [Qe7] afterward. However, this would run into } 2.e4! dxe4 3.Nxe4 { , and the bishop on [d6] is under attack. We should go forward and say that Black might simply capture on [e4] with } 3...Nxe4 { , but after } 4.Qxe4 { , it will be difficult for Black to play [c6]-[c5] in the next few moves. This is why White is better here. } ) 
2.Rac1 $5 { Placing the rook on the same file as the opponent's Queen is a healthy habit. } ( { The move ✓ } 2.e4 { doesn't have the same effect now: } 2...dxe4 3.Nxe4 c5 { , Black manages to play this important pawn break and solves their problems. } ) Qb8 $5 {[%csl Gb8]} { Not strictly necessary, but not a bad move. We prepare for the center to explode after possible pawn breaks. } ( {(✅ alternative)} 2...Rfe8 { is also possible, as after } 3.e4 { we would have the same sequence: } 3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 c5 { , solving the problems once again. } )  *

