{ This is a position from the game Van Wely – Short. It's a very instructive game in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White managed to put into practice the minority attack, and there are many pieces on the board, so try to figure out what to do next. } 
1.Rb6 $1 {[%cal Ba6g6]} {[%csl Gb6]} { There is more potential X-ray on the 6th rank, where Black's queen is located. White prevents Black's main idea ...[Qf6]. In the game, Black went for } ( { The automatic ✕ } 1.Rb7 Nxc3 2.Qxc3 Qf6 { leads nowhere. Moreover, the unprotected [b7]-rook can be an element for tactical ideas for Black. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.Bxe4?! dxe4 2.Nd2 { . We saw that it's actually dangerous to exchange this kind of knights, as Black improves their position with the [e4]-pawn becoming dangerous. } 2...Nh4! { , with the idea of …Qg6 and Black has potentially a strong attack. } ) Nxc3  ( { Both ❌ } 1...Qf6?? { and } { ❌ } {1...Qc7?? fail to 2.Nxd5! . } ) 
2.Qxc3  Qf6  {[%cal Rd7h3]} { Threatening ...[Bxh3] and White played the thematic } 
3.Bxg6 $1 {[%cal Gf3e5]} { Eliminating the dangerous knight, preparing [Ne5]. } Qxg6  {[%cal Rd7h3]} {[%csl Yg2]} ( 3... Qxg6 { If } 4.Ne5 { , than } 4...Rxe5 { followed by ...Bxh3, winning! } ) 
4.Kf1 $1 {[%cal Yg6g1]} {[%csl Re5]} {[%cal Gf3e5]} { And with [Ne5] threats later on, White had an advantage. } ( { ✅ } 4.Kh2 {(alternative is also possible, but)} { ✅ } {4.Kf1 was a more representative choice among Masters at the time. It is what Loek van Wely played in 2010. } )  *

