{ In the Dragon Variation of the Sicilian, we oftentimes might get this kind of double-edged position. Priority is to be as quick as possible when attacking the enemy king. How should White proceed? } 
1.h5 $1 ( { ✕ } 1.Bxg7 Kxg7 2.h5 g5! { . A typical blockading move. It will be hard for White to keep up with the attack. } ) b5  { Black has to go for counterplay. } ( { ✕ } 1...Bh8 2.Nd5! Qd8 {((Obviously not 2...Qxd2?? 3.Nxe7# . ))} 3.Nxf6+ Bxf6 4.Be3 { , and White will have a stable advantage here. } ) ( { ✕ } 1...Bxh6 2.Qxh6 g5 3.Nd5! { , and [g5] will be captured with a check. } ) 
2.hxg6  fxg6  
3.Bxg7  Kxg7  
4.Qh6+  Kf7  { White managed to penetrate along the h-file, but now comes another important pattern: } 
5.e5 $1 dxe5  
6.Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge4f6]} {[%cal Gh6h7]} {[%cal Ge4g5]} {[%csl Rf6]} {[%csl Rh7]} { Targeting the main defender: the [f6]-knight, with several threats, such as [Ng5]+, or [Nxf6] and [Qxh7]. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "5c) Exploit the Outpost on the Open File"]
[Black "5c) Exploit the Outpost on the Open File"]
