{ Even if the course is related to openings, we can see the effects of occupying the stronghold through this elementary position. There is only one move for White to win, and it should be the first move that comes to mind: } 
1.Rd5 $1 { White clearly has to evaluate the pawn endgame, but with a protected passed pawn after } Rxd5  
2.exd5 $1 {[%cal Gc4d5]} {[%cal Ge1e4]} {[%csl Gd5]} { it should be easily winning, as White also has the spare tempo with the move [g2]-[g3]. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "5c) Exploit the Outpost on the Open File"]
[Black "5c) Example 3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/1pqn2pp/p1pb1n2/3p1p2/3P1P2/P1NB1P1P/1P1Q1BP1/R3R1K1 w - - 0 1"]

{ This position has double f-pawns, coming from a [Bg4]-[Bxf3] lines or lines from Janowski's QGD. }  { White is strategically in danger, as Black has a majority on the queenside, 4 vs 3. One of the advantages of the double pawns is that the [e4]-square is covered on the open file for White, while [e5] is available. } 
1.Re5 $1 { It's the best moment to play this move. } ( { ✕ } 1.Bxf5 { eliminates the double pawns, but after } 1...Bxf4 { , and White is slightly worse because of their weak dark squares on the kingside. } ) ( { ✓ } 1.g3 { allows Black to exchange a pair of rooks, and after } 1...Rxe1+ 2.Rxe1 g6 { , the move } 3.Re5 { is less strong, as Black can capture and have the [Ne8]-[Ng7]-[Ne6] plan. } 3...Bxe5 4.fxe5 Ne8 { , and Black is doing great. } ) g6  { It seems that Black stabilized, but White has a powerful continuation. } ( { ❌ } 1...Bxe5 2.fxe5 +- { , Black is losing their knight directly. } ) 
2.g4 $1 { Thanks to the [e5]-rook, White has initiative. }  *

