{ It looks like an equal position, but White can fight for the open file first. How should it be done? } 
1.Rxd7 $3 { We should start with this move, let's see why. } ( { ✓ } 1.Bd5!? { is also possible, but not as precise as the [Rxd7] and [Bd5] sequence. } 1...Bxd5! 2.Rxd5! {((This would allow 2.cxd5 e4! , and now 3.Qg4 would be met by 3...Re8 , defending the pawn.))} 2...Rxd5 {(( 2...f6 3.e4 would give White an advantage, as there are four rooks on the board.))} 3.Rxd5! {(( 3.cxd5 e4! once again Black is fighting back. 4.Qg4 Qe7 ⩲ . ))} 3...f6 {(( 3...Rxd5?! would be a terrible decision, as after 4.cxd5 e4 5.Qg4! Qe7 6.Qc8 ± , White would be too active.))} 4.e4 ⩲ { , with only a pair of rooks left on the board, the advantage is less serious, as Black could decide to ignore the d-file at some point. } ) Rxd7  
2.Bd5 $1 { Only now we proceed with occupying the stronghold. } Bxd5  
3.cxd5 $16 {[%cal Ge3e4]} { Preparing [e3]-[e4]. } e4 $2 { This is now simply impossible because of the following queen move. } 
4.Qg4 $18 {[%csl Re4]}  *

