{ Several patterns in this course focus specifically on bishops, and this chapter is another example. Bishops can exert control over key squares along the open file from a distance. Typically, key squares are those where the opponent can stack pieces or, more generally, contest control of the file. The most common such square is on the first or eighth rank, but this isn’t always the case. As this is the most sophisticated pattern in the chapter, don’t force it at all costs – apply it when the position truly calls for it. } 
