1.Rxc8+ $1 { This move is based on concrete calculation. } ( { ✕ } 1.Rdc1?! { . There is a trick here, as Black can't answer by placing the knight on [c4] with check, } 1...Bd7! { . This patient move keeps Black in the game, as after all Black is a pawn up and [Nc4]+ is now a threat. } {(( 1...Nc4+? 2.R7xc4 bxc4 3.Ba4 +- , and Black will lose the [g4]-bishop. ))} 2.d6 Nc4+ 3.Bxc4 Rxc7 4.dxc7 bxc4 5.Rxc4 Rc8 { . } ) Bxc8  
2.f4 $1 { Only after playing this sequence will White eventually be able to control the c-file and be better. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "⭐ Part 6: Patterns of Harmony"]
[Black "Make Your Pieces Smile! – Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ The concept of harmony has lingered in my subconscious for quite some time. However, I truly grasped it when a friend, a strong player, told me that he considered me someone who places pieces harmoniously. 'Your pieces are always smiling,' he said. I wasn’t sure what he meant at first. Flattered as I was, I sensed there was something deeper to it. Achieving harmony can take many forms. My goal here is to present a few examples of harmonious play, helping you develop an instinct for spotting disharmony in a position – and fixing it. Ideally, it should become second nature, making you instinctively frown before setting things right. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "6a) Build a Strong Q+B Battery"]
[Black "6a) Build a Strong Q+B Battery"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N1BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 1"]

{ A queen-and-bishop battery is a common feature of harmonious positions. There are two typical setups: 🔹when the queen is behind the bishop, it usually indicates an intention to create strong threats, such as mating ideas; 🔹when the order is reversed, with the bishop behind the queen, the duo often aims to control key diagonals or squares for strategic purposes: restraining pawn pushes, attacking weak pawns, or providing squares for other pieces. } 
1.Qd2  { The latter setup is frequently seen in the opening phase, for example, with the active [Bd3]-[Qe2] development or the [Be3]-[Qd2] battery, which is used to challenge a fianchettoed bishop in the Dragon or, as in the present example, against the Pirc. Recognizing these possibilities will help us construct the right battery for the position. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "6a) Build a Strong Q+B Battery"]
[Black "6a) Example 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/p1n1pn2/8/3P4/P1NB1N2/1P3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 1"]

{ A must-know pattern in the IQP position. White has more space and can create the Q+B battery. } 
1.Bc2 $5 {[%cal Gd1d3]} { Building the [Qd3]-[Bc2] battery. } ( {(✅ alternative)} 1.Bb1 { is also possible, avoiding some [b4] pushes in the future when the battery is formed. } ) ( { ✅ } 1.Re1 { is another typical useful move in this position. The rook simply belongs to [e1]. } ) b5  
2.Qd3  {[%cal Gc1g5]} {[%csl Bc2]} {[%csl Bd3]} { White built the typical battery and will try to tickle Black with ideas such as [Bg5]. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "6a) Build a Strong Q+B Battery"]
[Black "6a) Example 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/pp1bbpp1/1nn1p2p/3pP3/3P4/P2BBN2/1P1NQPPP/2R1R1K1 w - - 0 1"]

{ This position arises from an Alapin, where Black hasn't managed to challenge White's center and, more importantly, has weakened the kingside. How should White exploit the [g7]-[h6] structure? } 
1.Bb1 $1 {[%cal Ge2d3]} {[%cal Gd3h7]} {[%csl Rh7]} { Building the Q+B battery with the queen ahead is very effective against the [g7]-[h6] structure, as [g6] is not possible because [h6] would be hanging. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "6a) Build a Strong Q+B Battery"]
[Black "6a) Example 3"]
