{ A position from the Four Knights Game with 4.d4 by White. This opening is generally considered quite annoying for Black, as White is extremely solid and knows what to do. Black can achieve harmony here with a well-coordinated setup, where the pieces work together to create problems for White. What option am I talking about? } Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7]} {[%cal Gb6f6]} {[%cal Gb6e6]} {[%csl Bb6]} { An elegant move, preparing [Bb7] with the rook already on [b6]. The bishop on [b7] will be x-raying the queen on [f3], while the [b6]-rook might have the option of transferring to the kingside. } ( { ✓ } 1...Re8 { is definitely possible. After } 2.Bg5 c6 3.Rfe1 { , we reach a standard position with the inclusion of ...[Rb8] – a move not really connected to ...[c7]-[c6] } )  *

