{ A scenario coming from the Delayed [Bxc6] Ruy López. White’s knight on [f5] might appear threatening, but with the typical regrouping, Black can prevent White's future threats and start their own play. How can Black achieve harmony? } Rf7 $1 {[%cal Ge7f8]} {[%cal Gg8h8]} {[%cal Ga6a5]} {[%cal Ga5a4]} {[%cal Gd7c5]} { I faced this in a game of mine with White, and despite being optimistic, I realized there is not so much for White here. Black defends [g7] and prepares ...[Bf8] and ...[Kh8]. Once these moves are made, Black can prepare their counterplay on the queenside, mainly by taking space with ....[a7]-[a5], ...[b7]-[b5] and so on. ...[Nc5]-...[Ne6] is also a possible maneuver, eyeing the [d4] potential landing square. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
