[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ " Pawns are the best weapon for fighting for the center. " That's why minor pieces are typically positioned behind them. However, when developing knights early on, we often place them in front of the pawns. Sometimes, regrouping these knights becomes a priority, especially when we want to give space to the pawns or avoid hindering the actions of other pieces, particularly bishops. This pattern is common when aiming for harmony, and it’s important to familiarize yourself with this concept, as it appears in several openings. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "6c) Reposition Your Knight Behind the Pawns"]
[Black "6c) Example 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1BP2N1P/PP1P1PP1/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 1"]

{ In this starting Ruy López position, one of the main variations, the Breyer is actually based on the retreating knight regrouping. } Nb8  
2.d4  Nbd7  {[%cal Gc7c5]} {[%cal Gc8b7]} {[%cal Gb7e4]} { The knight is harmoniously placed behind the pawns. There are at least two advantages: the c-pawn can now contribute to the fight for the center, and the [b7]-bishop will not be blocked. }  *

