{ A position from the Ragozin Defense, where the knight is once again on [c6], in front of the [c7]-pawn. Not always, these knights are out of play, though. How can Black justify the knight on [c6]? } dxc4 $1 { In general, it's a concession, but here it's connected to a thematic pawn push. } 
2.Bxc4  e5 $1 { Even if the [c6]-knight is in front of the [c7]-pawn, it's perfectly placed to support the ...[e6]-[e5] push, both protecting the pawn and putting pressure on [d4]. } 
3.d5  ( { ✅ } 3.dxe5 Nxe5 4.Nxe5 Qxe5 { . This is considered an equal position, as Black managed to eliminate White's center. } ) Ne7  {[%cal Gc7c6]} {[%cal Gf8d8]} {[%cal Gc8f5]} { and Black will have ideas of ...[c7]-[c6] in the future. }  *

