{ This comes from a slow 4.e3 Slav , where White captures the light-squared bishop on [g6]. Black is currently threatening [Bxg3]. How should White defend against it? } 
1.Kf2 $1 {[%cal Gf2g2]} {[%cal Ge3e1]} {[%cal Ge1h1]} {[%cal Gh1h3]} {[%cal Gh3e3]} { The king will be safe on [g2], covering empty space. } ( { A move like ❌ } 1.Bg2? { is not harmonious enough compared to the [Kg2]-[Be2]/[Bd3] configuration, and leads to the embarrassing tactic, } 1...Rxh2! 2.Rxh2 Bxg3+ 3.Ke2 Bxh2 { . } )  *

