{ This is a position from the French Tarrasch, where White decided to trade off queens early. How should Black continue his development? } e5 $1 { Black takes space in the center, preparing to develop the [c8]-bishop. I would say that in general the ...[e6]-[e5] move should be taken carefully, as it weakens the [d5]-square, but here Black can actually cover [d5] with their pieces. } ( { ✕ } 1...Bd7?! { would be a more classical way of developing the pieces, but there is a concrete problem after } 2.Bf3 Rab8 3.Re1 { , and White has the unpleasant threat of [Nf5]. } 3...g6 { this wouldn't help, as after } 4.Bg5! { . } ) 
2.Nb3  { White has several retreats, but Black will be able to develop their pieces regardless. } ( { ✓ } 2.Nc2 { , with the idea of [Ne3]-[d5], is not scary here. } 2...Be6 3.Ne3 Rhd8 { , and Black develop their pieces, as after [Bf3] there will be [e4]. } ) Be6  ( { ✕ } 2...b6 { , with the idea of ...Bb7, doesn't work because of } 3.Be3 Rb8 4.c5! { , and White gets activity against Black's uncoordinated pieces. } 4...bxc5 5.Na5! { . } ) 
3.c5 $6 { This move isn't a threat. } Bc7  { Black will have a nice [d5]-square for their minor pieces. }  *

