{ We are back again in the Giuoco Piano type of position. How would you deal with the [a7]-[g1] diagonal pressure as White? } 
1.a4 $1 {[%cal Ga1a2]} {[%csl Ba4]} {[%csl Bb4]} { White should hurry up with counterplay. Regarding the pressure along the [a1]-[g7] pressure, this is an exception, and White should hold on to the strong [f3]-knight. A resource for this purpose is the move [N1h2], which should be kept in mind. A potential [f4]-knight might be both ignored for a while, or eventually captured with the dark-squared bishop. By playing [a4], White intends to expand on the queenside, and the bishop on [a7] might become a target in case some lines will open up. } ( { ✕ } 1.g3?! { is the move that comes naturally to me in this kind of position, but it is actually too slow. Some of my fellow chess players friends mock me because [g3]-[Kg2] is my favorite plan in many positions. However, we shouldn't get obsessed with our ideas. The move [g3] is weakening the f-file, and Black will double, causing a lot of pressure. } )  *

