{ ‘Transforming bishops into snipers’ means keeping them safe from vulnerable squares. Bishops love to keep the action under control, without being the main character, but only intervene when there is something concrete to collect. Developing an instinct for keeping them away from the main battle zone will help protect them and maximize their effectiveness. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "6e) Transform Your Bishops into Snipers"]
[Black "6e) Example 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1qr1r1k1/1b1nbppp/pp1ppn2/8/1PPNP3/P1N1BP2/3QB1PP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 1"]

{ We have a classical Hedgehog position. We saw that Black has an option of playing the ...[Bd8]-...[Bc7] maneuver. The ...[d5] break is there, and White has to pay close attention to its consequences. We can see that the move ...[Rfe8] is meant to X-ray both White's bishops. That's why we want to find a safe location for our them. } 
1.Bf1 $1 {[%cal Ge3f2]} {[%csl Bf1]} {[%csl Bf2]} { An automatic prophylactic move. From the [f1]-square, the bishop does the same job as from [e2]: controls the [f1]-[a6] diagonal and eyes the [a6]-weak pawn in case of eventual openings of the center via ...[d6]-[d5] break, for example. On [f1], the bishop is safer. We can make a point for [Bf2] being a future possibility, although the bishop from [e3] has the option to move on [f4], if needed. However, developing the harmonious intuition for a move like [Bf2] is exactly what we want to learn here! }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "6e) Transform Your Bishops into Snipers"]
[Black "6e) Example 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/8/4P3/1NN5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 1"]

{ We are in the Sicilian Dragon universe. White decided to take it slow and castle kingside, avoiding potential races in opposite-castled kings scenarios. There are several possibilities here, but one of them is connected to our topic. } 
1.Re1 $5 { A generally useful move, preparing [Nd5] followed by [exd5] in case of Black's ...[Nxd5], so the [e1]-rook would be on a semi-open file. Black has several options, but one of the main options is what follows. } a6  { A typical Sicilian useful move. Black wants to expand on the queenside. } ( { ✅ } 1...Be6 { is another, although less accurate, continuation. } ) 
2.Bf1  {[%cal Gc3d5]} {[%cal Ge1e4]} {[%csl Gf1]} {[%csl Be4]} { White is ready to play [Nd5]. This is generally 'spiced up' by the move [Bg5], applying even more pressure on the [f6]-knight. } Bg4 $5 { In my Classical English course, this is my recommendation against the reversed Dragon setup based on, guess what, ...[Re8]-...[Bf8] plan! An annoying move. Black doesn't fight for advantage, but it's a typical motif, allowing Black to equalize. }  *

