{ We are once again in a Caro-Kann structure. This position, however, is reached through the Fort Knox order, where Black exchanged their light-squared bishop to be able to play ...[c7]-[c6]. White has the bishop pair, but once again, in case of pawn breaks in the center, bishops might become targets. } 
1.c3 $5 { Not necessarily the absolute best move here, but the idea is pretty simple: we want our bishop to be repositioned behind the pawn. They aim to put pressure on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal, so whether it's on [d3] or on [c2], doesn't really matter. On [c2] though, the bishop will feel much safer. Potential pawn breaks from Black's side lose power, as now White can simply eliminate the tension, remaining with the bishop pair advantage in an open position. } O-O  
2.Bc2  {[%cal Gh2h4]} {[%csl Gc1]} {[%csl Gc2]} { As masterfully illustrated in the Mauricio Rios's book Chess Structures – a Grand Master Guide, presented here on Chessable by GM Peter-Heine Nielsen, White's plan is generally connected to the kingside [h2]-[h4]-[h5] expansion. }  *

