{ A position from a Nimzo-Indian-type opening, where Black exchanged their dark-squared bishop for some central control and smooth development. However, White has two bishops and proceeds with the typical idea. Which one? } 
1.Ne1  {[%cal Gf2f3]} {[%cal Ge1d3]} {[%csl Yb7]} {[%csl Bd3]} {[%csl Ye4]} { This, or [Nd2], should come to mind automatically in this kind of position. Once the knight is behind the f-pawn, White can challenge the [e4]-knight with [f2]-[f3], limiting the [b7]-bishop too we will look at this idea in the next chapter of the course. Moreover, the knight has a sweet [d3]-square available, which is a plus. I would also add, as rule of thumb, that in a situation of B+B+K vs K+K+B, it is preferable for the B+B side not to exchange the only knight. This idea clearly has exceptions, but here I would prefer [Ne1] to [Nd2]. } ( { ✕ } 1.Rfe1 { is an inaccuracy, as now [Ne1] is not possible. } {( ✓ 1.Rfd1 is possible, but still not the priority in this position. )} )  *

