{ This structure has been popular for quite some time, as after queens' exchange and doubling the pawns on the e-file, Black seems to get quite an easy play on the queenside by pushing ...[b7]-[b5] and so on. However, White's thematic move counters these plans and provides White a solid advantage in the long run. What is this move? } 
1.Nb1 $1 { White improves their only bad piece, and now any advancing on the queenside can be challenged by pawn breaks for example, ...[b7]-[b5] can be challenged by [a2]-[a4], and White can exploit the potentially weakened squares. The fact that after [Nb4], White has to play, [Kd1] is irrelevant, as eventually, the king will hide on [c2] by playing [c2]-[c3], and without queens, there is little Black can do to exploit it. }  *

