{ Seemingly a typical position for the Giuoco Piano. However, the Niemann-Kramnik team came up with a powerful concept for White. Can you guess the idea? } 
1.Bd2 $5 {[%cal Gd1c1]} {[%cal Gd2h6]} { While [Bb3], or [b4] would be the natural moves here, White ignores the ...[Na5] threat, prioritizing the preparation of the [Bd2]-[Qc1] battery. } Na5  
2.Bb3  { Yes, White gives up the bishop pair, but it's not such a big deal here. } ( { ✅ } 2.Bd5!? { is another cool response, with the idea of meeting } 2...c6 { with } 3.Bxf7+ Kxf7 4.b4 { , gaining back the piece, after having weakened Black's king. } ) Nxb3  
3.axb3  {[%cal Gf1g3]} {[%cal Gd1c1]} { Ng3 and [Qc1] are going to be the next moves, with a potential attack on the kingside. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "Part 6 Test"]
[Black "6) Test #10"]
