{ A position from Jobava London with [e6]. Black can proceed in several ways. What would you prioritize to be the most harmonious? } Rac8 $5 {[%cal Ga8c8]} {[%cal Gf8d8]} {[%cal Ga6b8]} { In my opinion this should be the priority. We place the rooks on [c8] and [d8]. In case of [Ne5] only then! we reroute the knight from [a6] to [b8] and [c6]. With the rook on [c8], we can think about taking on [d4] and potential jumps to [e4]. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "⭐ Part 7: Patterns of Pawns’ Play"]
[Black "Essential Pawn Patterns – Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ " Pawns are the soul of chess. – François-André Danican Philidor " As the least valuable piece, a pawn can make a big difference. The higher the level of play, the smaller the details that decide games. Often, a single pawn advantage is enough to secure victory. With such fine margins, mastering pawn play is essential. In this part of the course, we will explore five valuable pawn motifs. Pawn moves define structures in the opening, and I have selected these five patterns because they are the easiest to incorporate into your games. Understanding these mechanisms will help you recognize them instinctively and apply them automatically. As always, the goal is to internalize these patterns until they become second nature. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "7a) Restrict Enemy Pieces"]
[Black "7a) Restrict the Enemy Pieces"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Since the pawn is the least valuable piece, any time it can neutralize a minor piece or more while maintaining balance, it's a huge success. Minor pieces dislike being restricted by pawns, as their value drops. I have a funny story about this concept of restriction. At one of the workshops I've been part of, White had pawns on [a2] and [b3]. A player suggested the move …Nd7–Nb6, but everyone objected, saying, 'That doesn’t make sense: the knight is limited by the pawn!' However, our hero countered with, 'Actually, my knight is limiting the [b3]-pawn!' Of course, things weren’t quite that simple in that case, but the idea that a piece worth three points can restrict a piece worth one is certainly unusual. Let’s look at a few examples to illustrate this concept. } 
1.--   *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "7a) Restrict Enemy Pieces"]
[Black "7a) Example 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/8/1P3N2/PBPPPPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 1"]

{ There are several possibilities for Black here, clearly, as we are on move 3 in this Nimzowitsch-Larsen Attack. However, even at such an early stage, it is possible to implement the limiting strategy by restricting both the bishop on [b2] and the knight on [f3]. } f6 $1 { The last White's move, 3.Nf3 wasn't indeed precise. Now Black threatens to expand in the center with the move [e5], too. } 
2.c4 $6 { Just to explain what limiting at its best means. } d4  
3.e3  e5  {[%csl Rb2]} {[%csl Rf3]} { The bishop on [b2] is terrible against the pawn chain, as it's hard to challenge it. Definitely not the kind of opening outcome you want for your pieces! }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "7a) Restrict Enemy Pieces"]
[Black "7a) Example 2"]
