[FEN "r2qkb1r/1bpp1ppp/p1n2n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]

{ The 'old Arkhangelsk' with the bishop on [b7] was popular in the 90s, but nowadays, it doesn't have a great reputation. Why? } 
1.d3 $1 {[%cal Yb7e4]} {[%cal Yf6e4]} { The [d3]-concept is considered to be critical, as it limits the bishop on [b7]. White will keep the center closed and will try to exploit the weakness of the [f5]-square now that the bishop is on [b7] later on, by regrouping a knight via [d2]-[f1]-[g3], or [e3], targeting the [f5]-square. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
[White "7a) Restrict Enemy Pieces"]
[Black "7a) Example 3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/pp2bpnp/2p2npB/3pN3/3P4/2NBP2P/PPQ2PP1/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]

{ Coming from a Carlsbad structure, Black rerouted the knight to [g7], in order to prepare the move ...[Bf5], exchanging the light bishops, which would usually mean that Black solves opening problems. How to proceed with White? } 
1.g4 $3 {[%cal Yg7f5]} {[%cal Yg7h5]} {[%csl Yc8]} {[%csl Yf6]} {[%csl Gg4]} {[%csl Rg7]} { This ambitious move is justified here for a couple of reasons: the first one is pretty logical, as the pawn prevents the ...[Bf5] idea from Black, limiting the [g7]-knight, together with the [c8]-bishop and the [f6]-knight. The second reason is that this pawn is difficult to challenge, as the bishop on [h6] prevents a potential ...[h7]-[h5]. }  *

