{ A position where White has the bishop pair, possibly from a Nimzo-Indian-type structure. Black clearly hasn’t equalized, with the bishop on [c6] blocked by the [c7]-pawn. White can proceed in several ways, but what should come to mind at this point? } 
1.f3 $1 {[%csl Rc6]} {[%csl Rf6]} { threatening the positional [e3]-[e4] domination. } ( {(✅ alternative)} 1.Qc3!? { is also a good move, pinning the [f6]-knight. } ) ( { ✕ } 1.e4 { allows unnecessary complications after } 1...Bxe4! { . } ) Nd5 $1 { Preparing to jump on [f4] in case of [e3]-[e4]. } 
2.Bd4 $1 { White has an advantage thanks to good central control too. } ( { ✓ } 2.e4 { allows } 2...Nf4 { , and Black will bring the knight on [e6], fighting. } )  *

