{ Once again, we’re looking at a position arising from the Carlsbad pawn structure. White has a nice knight on [e5], but it is about to be challenged with ...[f7]-[f6]. How can we think about limiting enemy pieces? } 
1.f5 $1 {[%csl Rc8]} {[%csl Rf8]} { A typical move, restricting both the [f8]-knight and the [c8]-bishop. The fact that the [e5]-square is now not under big control is not so relevant. } ( { ❌ } 1.g4? { would simply lose the [g4]-pawn after } 1...f6 ∓ { . } ) ( { ❌ } 1.b3?! { limits the [b6]-knight, but it's not that important. After } 1...f6 2.Nf3 { , Black can develop their light-squared bishop with } 2...Bg4! { , getting some counterplay. } )  *

