{ Several openings include the moves [Nxf6], [Nxc6], ...Nxc3 or …Nxf3. This creates an isolated rook a- or h-pawn. Pushing this pawn is actually logical because, in the opening, central pawns are generally more valued, and rook pawns are used to take space or to disturb enemy coordination. Pushing the pawn forward two, or even three squares can have a big effect and disrupt enemy plans, creating counterplay. When you have no more urgent tasks, advancing the isolated a- or h-pawn should feel natural. } 
1.--   *

