{ The most iconic isolated pawn push in my opinion can be found in the Sicilians where White capture on [c6]. Later on, Black plays ...[d7]-[d5], and White, at some point, can push [e5], closing the center. At this point, pushing the a-pawn can have several benefits. } a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4]} {[%cal Ga8b8]} {[%cal Gb8b2]} {[%cal Yb2b3]} {[%cal Ba4b3]} {[%csl Bb3]} { The a-pawn will restrict White's pawns on the queenside and will take away some squares such as [a4], once it gets pushed there. In case of ...[Rb8], White can stop the pressure on the b-file by playing [b3], and at that point the a-pawn reaching [a4] can put additional pressure. }  *

[Event "Healthy Opening Habits for Middlegame Success"]
