{ In a Symmetrical Grünfeld, Black played ...[e7]-[e6], reinforcing the center, but putting the [f5]-bishop in an unsafe position. There is definitely ...[Nbd7] as a developing move, but the [b8]-knight might jump on [a6], if White decides to play c4-c5 and force Qxb3 axb3. How can Black solve the [f5]-bishop issue on the kingside and achieve harmony? } h6 $1 {[%cal Gg6g5]} {[%cal Gf5g6]} {[%csl Gf5]} { A thematic move, preparing [g6]-[g5], giving more space for the [f5]-bishop. } ( { This is a normal move, but allows White to build the h3-g4 idea first by playing } 1...Nbd7 2.h3 { . } ) ( { ✓ } 1...Qxb3?! 2.axb3 Bc2 3.b4 { and White has interesting prospects on the queenside connected to [b4]-[b5]. } )  *

