{ This is a position from the Caro-Kann Exchange Variation, where Black decided to play …g6 followed by …Bf5. The bishop on [g7] is actually misplaced, and in general, a better option is to play …g6 and …Bf5, but follow up with [e6]-[Bd6]. White is considered to have an edge here. How should White reorganize their minor pieces? } 
1.Ne5 $1 { An extra plus is that White doesn't allow the ...[b7]-[b5] counterplay. } ( { ✓ } 1.Ne1 b5! { , and Black can sometimes even sac the b-pawn, as the [g7]-bishop would open up. } ) e6  ( { ✓ } 1...Nxe5 2.dxe5! { . This is in general an improvement for White, as the [e5]-pawn takes away some squares, and, more importantly, White gets control of the [d4]-square. } ) 
2.Nd3 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3]} {[%csl Bd3]} { The knight on [d3] is powerful and [b7]-[b5] now is hard to achieve, as [b4] is more controlled, and the [c5]-square will be available. White will slowly improve and be better. A potential plan, in the long run, could be [Nfe5], [f3] and [g2]-[g4], targeting the [f5]-pawn. }  *

