{ In the Queen's Gambit Accepted, instead of the most modern lines connected to [e6]+c5, Black has an option to go with an early …Bg4. Here, White expanded on the kingside and captured the bishop on [g6]. How can White achieve harmony? } 
1.Bf1 $5 {[%csl Gf1]} {[%csl Gg2]} { Repositioning the bishop on the [h1]-[a8] diagonal is the most played move here, and for a good reason. The bishop will be powerful, and will guard the kingside. } ( { ✅ } 1.Qf3 { is an alternative, having in mind [Kf1]-[Kg2]. However, this allows the immediate } 1...b5 2.Bb3 c5 { , and White has to deal with immediate complications. } ) c6  
2.Bg2  {[%cal Ge1g1]} {[%cal Gd4d5]} {[%cal Ge3e4]} { After [O-O], White's king will be quite safe, as it's hard to build a Q+B battery for Black on the [b8]-[h2] diagonal. The [e4]-[d5] plan, in the long run, opening the long diagonal, is on White's agenda. }  *

