{ A position from possibly a London System, or Exchange Variation Caro-Kann. White has just played 1.Rae1 , with clear intentions of playing [Ne5], followed by [f4]. Try to dive into the position, and suggest the most harmonious way to proceed for Black. } Rfb8 $3 {[%cal Gb7b5]} {[%cal Ga7a5]} { Preparing the main strategic [b7]-[b5] plan is best with the rooks on [a8]-[b8], once White decided to play [Rae1], placing the rooks away from the queenside. } ( { ✓ } 1...Qc7 { is a healthy move, enabling the capture on [e5], as now there is no fork after [dxe5]. } ) ( { ✓ } 1...Rab8 { is another natural possibility, aiming at placing the rooks on [b8] and [c8]. However, after } 2.Qc2 {(( 2.a3 Rfc8 3.Qa2 is also possible, avoiding all ideas along the c-file with the queen on [c2].))} 2...Rfc8 3.Nb3! b5?! {(( 3...Nb4 4.Qd2 Nxd3 5.Qxd3 is possible for Black, although [b7]-[b5] now is going to be hard to achieve, but Black can switch to calm play with [b6].))} 4.a3! { Black doesn't have the possibility to play } 4...a5? { as after } 5.Nxc6! { , the [a5]-pawn is unprotected. } ) 
2.Qc2  b5  
3.Nb3  a5 $36 { Black is quick with the play on the queenside. }  *

