{ A position from the Kan Variation e6+Nc6+a6, where White took on [c6]. What should Black do on the queenside? } a5 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} { Before playing [c6]-[c5], Black remains solid with the [c6]-[d5] center, aiming on exchanging bishops first. } ( { ✅ } 1...c5 2.c4! { , putting pressure in the center and preserving the light-squared bishops. } 2...d4 { . This has to be played. } 3.Qg4 { , White's attack can be more unpleasant with the [d3]-bishop alive. Black is still quite solid, but I wouldn't like to close the center so early. } ) 
2.c4  Ba6  ( { In case of ✓ } 2...dxc4 3.Bc2! { , Black would destroy their own center without a reason. } ) 
3.b3  Nc5  ( { ✅ } 3...Bb4 4.Re3 f5! { makes more sense now that Black's center is still alive, although [f7]-[f5] is not an easy move to play. } ) 
4.Nxc5  Bxc5  
5.Qh5  g6  
6.Qh3  a4  {[%cal Ga4b3]} {[%cal Ga6c4]} {[%csl Rb3]} {[%csl Rc4]} { Black has counterplay on the queenside, while for White it's not that easy to organize an attack on the kingside. }  *

